Renders a `TypedEntry` (from `crate::expand`) into an LSP snippet body for editor-side expansion, as an alternative output target to `crate::render`'s Plover-keystroke rendering. Because the editor's snippet engine (`vim.snippet`, VS Code, etc.) owns cursor placement via tabstops, this file does none of `render`'s movement math, closer-dropping, or plain/smart split — landings become `${n}` tabstops directly.

Landings are renumbered from arbitrary indices into LSP tab order: `sorted_landings` collects and dedups all `Chunk::Landing(n)` values ascending, then `tab_index` maps the *highest* landing to `${0}` (LSP's mandatory final exit) and the rest to `${1}`, `${2}`, … in ascending order — not in template order. If a landing index doesn't appear in `sorted` (shouldn't happen), `tab_index` silently falls back to `0` rather than panicking.

Two render paths, chosen by `entry.terminal` in `render_snippet`: `render_terminal` emits tabstops and honors `entry.one_liner` (suppresses `Chunk::BodyBreak` newlines when true); `render_non_terminal` strips brackets from literal text via `strip_brackets`/`is_bracket` and silently drops `Chunk::Brace`, `Newline`, `BodyBreak`, and `Landing` chunks — these are "irreversible" and treated as not needed for an intermediate partial. Any other unresolved chunk type reaching either path (e.g. a chunk that should have been resolved upstream in `expand`) produces `Err(SnippetError)` via `unresolved()`, naming the chunk kind.

`esc()` escapes `\`, `$`, and `}` for literal text in the LSP snippet grammar — required because `$` and `}` are syntactically significant (tabstop syntax) and unescaped literal text containing them would corrupt the body. `push_brace` follows the same LSP quirk: a lone `{` is literal and passes through unescaped, but `}` must always be escaped to `\}` since it would otherwise be read as closing a placeholder.

`SENTINEL_OPEN`/`SENTINEL_CLOSE` (both `"@@"`) wrap the stroke's `key_id` in the token Plover actually types, so the companion Neovim plugin can locate and expand it without colliding with real text — this sentinel format must stay in sync with that nvim plugin's parsing logic.

`build_snippets(entries: &[TypedEntry]) -> Result<SnippetBuild, SnippetError>` is the entry point used by callers assembling both output artifacts: `plover_keys` (stroke → sentinel-wrapped token) and `snippets` (key_id → LSP body), using `OrderedMap` from `crate::json_out` to preserve insertion order for deterministic output. It also detects collisions — the same `key_id` rendering to two different bodies from different entries — collecting offending keys into `collisions` rather than erroring; callers must check this list themselves, as `build_snippets` does not fail on collision, it only reports it (last-writer-wins in the map, since `insert` still overwrites).